{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Xp62o3mBaS65agrDRtPHG4","type":"tool_result","content":"   118→  have h_conv : ∀ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) = if j = ⟨0, hd0⟩ then 1 else 0 :=\n   119→    fun j => by simp [Fin.ext_iff]\n   120→  simp_rw [h_conv]\n   121→  -- Apply sum_ite_eq: ∑ j in univ, if j = a then f j else 0 = if a ∈ univ then f a else 0\n   122→  simp [Finset.sum_ite_eq]\n   123→\n   124→/-- **THEOREM 3: E88 supports S·q content-based retrieval that E1H cannot**\n   125→\n   126→We formally demonstrate E88's content-addressable retrieval by constructing:\n   127→- A state S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (outer product of the first standard basis vector)\n   128→- Two queries e₀ ≠ e₁ (orthogonal basis vectors)\n   129→- S · e₀ = e₀ (nonzero: retrieves the stored association)\n   130→- S · e₁ = 0   (zero: orthogonal query finds nothing)\n   131→\n   132→So different queries retrieve different information from the same state.\n   133→\n   134→**Why E1H cannot do this**: E1H's state is a D-vector h, not a matrix.\n   135→Any \"read\" operation on h produces the same information (or a fixed linear\n   136→projection thereof) regardless of any \"query\" vector — there is no matrix\n   137→to multiply against, so no key-based addressing is possible.\n   138→\n   139→This difference explains why E88 can implement associative memory patterns\n   140→(key-value retrieval) that E1H fundamentally cannot. -/\n   141→theorem e88_addressable_e1h_not (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   142→    ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n   143→      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧ e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ e88ContentRead S q₂ := by\n   144→  have hd0 : 0 < d := by omega\n   145→  have hd1 : 1 < d := by omega\n   146→  -- Standard basis vectors: e₀ = 1 at index 0, e₁ = 1 at index 1\n   147→  let e₀ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 0 then 1 else 0\n   148→  let e₁ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 1 then 1 else 0\n   149→  -- E88 state: S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (rank-1 outer product storing e₀ → e₀ association)\n   150→  let S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ := Matrix.of (fun i j => e₀ i * e₀ j)\n   151→  use S, e₀, e₁\n   152→  constructor\n   153→  · -- e₀ ≠ e₁: they differ at index 0 (e₀(0) = 1, e₁(0) = 0)\n   154→    intro h\n   155→    have h00 := congr_fun h ⟨0, hd0⟩\n   156→    simp only [e₀, e₁] at h00\n   157→    norm_num at h00\n   158→  · -- e88ContentRead S e₀ ≠ e88ContentRead S e₁\n   159→    -- We show they differ at coordinate 0:\n   160→    --   (S · e₀)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₀)[0] = e₀[0] · ‖e₀‖² = 1 · 1 = 1\n   161→    --   (S · e₁)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₁)[0] = e₀[0] · (e₀ · e₁) = 1 · 0 = 0\n   162→    intro h_reads_eq\n   163→    -- Compute (S · e₀) at index 0 = 1\n   164→    have h_read0 : e88ContentRead S e₀ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 1 := by\n   165→      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S,\n   166→                 Matrix.of_apply, e₀, Fin.val_mk]\n   167→      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1 else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) *\n   168→      --                                          (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0)\n   169→      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1)²  = 1 * 1 = 1\n   170→      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n   171→      exact basis_self_inner_product d hd0\n   172→    -- Compute (S · e₁) at index 0 = 0\n   173→    have h_read1 : e88ContentRead S e₁ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 0 := by\n   174→      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S,\n   175→                 Matrix.of_apply, e₀, e₁, Fin.val_mk]\n   176→      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1)\n   177→      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1) = 1 * 0 = 0\n   178→      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n   179→      exact basis_inner_product_zero d hd0 hd1\n   180→    -- Contradiction: from h_reads_eq, 1 = 0\n   181→    have := congr_fun h_reads_eq ⟨0, hd0⟩\n   182→    rw [h_read0, h_read1] at this\n   183→    norm_num at this\n   184→\n   185→/-! ## Part 3: Capacity Separation -/\n   186→\n   187→/-- **THEOREM 4: Capacity Separation**\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6cd06645-8a00-4465-88a4-569f84504161","uuid":"165f968e-a918-4116-ade4-f1c6dd9bcdf1","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E88ExceedsE1HCapacity.lean","content":"  have h_conv : ∀ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) = if j = ⟨0, hd0⟩ then 1 else 0 :=\n    fun j => by simp [Fin.ext_iff]\n  simp_rw [h_conv]\n  -- Apply sum_ite_eq: ∑ j in univ, if j = a then f j else 0 = if a ∈ univ then f a else 0\n  simp [Finset.sum_ite_eq]\n\n/-- **THEOREM 3: E88 supports S·q content-based retrieval that E1H cannot**\n\nWe formally demonstrate E88's content-addressable retrieval by constructing:\n- A state S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (outer product of the first standard basis vector)\n- Two queries e₀ ≠ e₁ (orthogonal basis vectors)\n- S · e₀ = e₀ (nonzero: retrieves the stored association)\n- S · e₁ = 0   (zero: orthogonal query finds nothing)\n\nSo different queries retrieve different information from the same state.\n\n**Why E1H cannot do this**: E1H's state is a D-vector h, not a matrix.\nAny \"read\" operation on h produces the same information (or a fixed linear\nprojection thereof) regardless of any \"query\" vector — there is no matrix\nto multiply against, so no key-based addressing is possible.\n\nThis difference explains why E88 can implement associative memory patterns\n(key-value retrieval) that E1H fundamentally cannot. -/\ntheorem e88_addressable_e1h_not (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧ e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ e88ContentRead S q₂ := by\n  have hd0 : 0 < d := by omega\n  have hd1 : 1 < d := by omega\n  -- Standard basis vectors: e₀ = 1 at index 0, e₁ = 1 at index 1\n  let e₀ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 0 then 1 else 0\n  let e₁ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 1 then 1 else 0\n  -- E88 state: S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (rank-1 outer product storing e₀ → e₀ association)\n  let S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ := Matrix.of (fun i j => e₀ i * e₀ j)\n  use S, e₀, e₁\n  constructor\n  · -- e₀ ≠ e₁: they differ at index 0 (e₀(0) = 1, e₁(0) = 0)\n    intro h\n    have h00 := congr_fun h ⟨0, hd0⟩\n    simp only [e₀, e₁] at h00\n    norm_num at h00\n  · -- e88ContentRead S e₀ ≠ e88ContentRead S e₁\n    -- We show they differ at coordinate 0:\n    --   (S · e₀)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₀)[0] = e₀[0] · ‖e₀‖² = 1 · 1 = 1\n    --   (S · e₁)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₁)[0] = e₀[0] · (e₀ · e₁) = 1 · 0 = 0\n    intro h_reads_eq\n    -- Compute (S · e₀) at index 0 = 1\n    have h_read0 : e88ContentRead S e₀ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 1 := by\n      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S,\n                 Matrix.of_apply, e₀, Fin.val_mk]\n      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1 else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) *\n      --                                          (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0)\n      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1)²  = 1 * 1 = 1\n      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n      exact basis_self_inner_product d hd0\n    -- Compute (S · e₁) at index 0 = 0\n    have h_read1 : e88ContentRead S e₁ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 0 := by\n      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S,\n                 Matrix.of_apply, e₀, e₁, Fin.val_mk]\n      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1)\n      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1) = 1 * 0 = 0\n      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n      exact basis_inner_product_zero d hd0 hd1\n    -- Contradiction: from h_reads_eq, 1 = 0\n    have := congr_fun h_reads_eq ⟨0, hd0⟩\n    rw [h_read0, h_read1] at this\n    norm_num at this\n\n/-! ## Part 3: Capacity Separation -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 4: Capacity Separation**","numLines":70,"startLine":118,"totalLines":284}}}
